'''Tanaka Funamoriyama Kofun''' (田中・舟森山古墳) is a [[Zenpō-kōhō-fun]] located within the {{ill|Oguni Foothills Kofun Group|ja|雄国山麓古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kitakata City|ja|喜多方市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan.

== Overview ==

The current mound has an elliptical shape but is significantly deformed due to its location within a residential area. The original form of the mound has been substantially altered, with the apex heavily leveled. Although the frontal section is now lost, it is believed that the mound originally had a frontal section, suggesting it was either a [[Zenpō-kōhō-fun]] (Square-Front Rear-Square Mound) or a [[Zenpō-kōen-fun]] (Keyhole-shaped Mound). If the former, it would represent the largest Zenpō-kōhō-fun in the Tōhoku region.

A trial excavation conducted by the Shinkawa Town Board of Education revealed the presence of a clay burial chamber (''nenkaku'') at the apex of the mound. Based on haniwa and {{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft|12=draft}} artifacts excavated from the site, the mound's construction is estimated to date to the 4th century.

== References ==

* Tsuji, Hidetoshi. ''Tōhoku Kofun Research Origins: The Aizu Ōtsukayama Kofun''. Series: "Learning from Sites" 029, Shinseisha, 2006.
== See Also ==

* {{ill|List of Kofun in Japan|ja|日本の古墳一覧|12=draft|12=draft}}

